727750f-b.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 57th Avenue
727750f-b.text:
Queens Boulevard, north side, west from Fifty-seventh Ave., showing
in their order from fore to background, Nos. 85,79,63 and 49 Queens
Boulevard and which were demolished when the Boulevard was widened in
1924. No. 63 belonged to Mrs. Bauch from 1873 to 1891 and No. 49 to
Mrs. Raymond. View No. 2 of this set is similar, eliminating No. 85.
February 1924.
View 2: February 11, 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727746f-b.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 57th Avenue
727746f-b.text:
Qlueens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 57th Avenue, showing
the Samuel Reime House, a pre-Revolutionary house. It was also
known as the Arnold's House. One Bretonier was the owner in 1852.
The house was altered in 1865. Eugene L. Armbruster is authority
for the above data.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  Views 1,2: Oct., 1928
MAY BE REPRODUCED  View 3: Sept., 1934
View 4: P. L. Sperr  June 29, 1936

727748f-b.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 57th Avenue
727748f-b.text:
Queens Boulevard, west from Fifty-seventh Avenue, showing an
area of OQueens Boulevard prior to its widening. View No. 1 shows in
the foreground No. 58 (old No.) Queens Boulevard at the S.W. corner of
above Boulevard and Fifty-sixth Avenue. It was the property of one
Arnoldi prior to 1873. Also seen in this view is the steeple of the
new First Presbyterian Church of Newtown. Its steeple has since been
rem;oved. View No. 2 shows the north side of the Boulevard. The ex-
tension of Mrs. Raymond's house at the right foreground is west of Fifty-
sixth ..venue. (Laconia Street also known as Horsebrook Road). View.
No. 3 shows the hhouse alone prior to its removal. View Ho. 2 also
shows the old First Presbyterian Church in the background. View No. 4
shows the house according to E.L. Arbruster to now, 1925, be on the
north (west) side of Fifty-seventh Avenue (Caldwell Avenue) about 50
feet west (south) of Van Horn Street. However it does not appear in
the 1929 Atlas of Queens County.
April 1923.
View 2: August 1924.
View 3: February , 1924.
View 4: July 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
